< review>
Over three years ago I'd had enough of my excessive weight.  I thought I'd tried everything...except Medifast.  I went into the El Cajon office, spoke with the supervisor, got a feel for the place, people, and program and decided to try it.  That was the best decision I'd made in a long time.  My counselor was Mary, and she helped me loose my goal of 71 pounds.  To my great surprise, I ended up loosing 93, and felt great!!!  I was able to maintain my weight for two years, but this last summer I allowed outside stressors to take over again, and decided I needed to get a handle on it before it got a handle on me.  I'd only gained back 10 pounds, but it was enough, so I went back.  I reactivated my plan, and am currently working with Crystal.  Both coaches have been absolutely wonderful, and I would recommend Medifast to anyone and everyone who is interested.  It doesn't matter if you have 100 pounds to loose or 10.  The program can work for everyone.  I like the food, and I thrive in the stricter environment (in terms of allowed/not allowed foods).  It allows me to adjust my eating habits to good ones, and gives me enough time to get the cravings of sugars out of my mind/body.  The body analysis that they conduct also allow you to see how any change you make in your diet can effect your body.  I have relost those 10 pounds and am maintaining again!<//review>

<user_id>108723545641636438865</user_id><name>R Dibb<//name><time>1372362255386<//time>< rating>
5< /rating>
< Text>
I can't say enough positive about this center and our experience overall with Medifast.

First, to eliminate some confusion, this is NOT attending group meetings where you report back. This is NOT an all liquid diet. Each weekly session with your counselor is private, informative and never rushed.

My wife and daughter signed up and then left for a college tour. One week later, I decided I'd support them and I signed up too. We all ended up with Nikki as our counselor. We all can't say enough good about her! She's great! But please don't think this means the other counselors aren't equally as good because they are. All of the people at this facility are exceptional.

We all lost out weight at about the same rate. I have reached my goal weight and am in the transitional phase.

The center and the counselors do a great job of keeping you motivated. If your weight loss slows, they know exactly what to do to mix it up. With their body composition scanner, if your muscle mass drops, they know exactly how to adjust your meals to maintain your muscle and eliminate just the fat.

FOOD:
We like all of the food with only a couple of exceptions, but the selection is more than adequate. You won't get bored with the food. There's plenty of variety and preparation options for their meals. With the assistance of our counselor, we have become very creative with our own prepared 'lean and green' meal.

REFERRALS:
Many of our friends have seen our success and that has promoted three so far to sign up for Medifast. They are happy they did and have also had success.<//Text>

<review>This business over the years has been up and a little down.  Sometimes really good, other times decent.

< review>
For sfo, from Fremont this is the best way to commute. Plenty of parking but you need to Rush early in the morning so that you can get a spot to park your car.
BART Staff are so friendly and helpful when there is an issue with your clipper card or a vending machine.
We have the bus transit right in front to go anywhere in the Fremont.< /review>

<userid>107767768560438055175< /userid><Date>1481675437819<//Date><Review>Welcome to the neighborhood, Duchess!

With a female owner and female chef, this place is girl power done right. Come in for a cocktail stay for the food, and make sure to check out the beer and wine list. Caroline, co-owner and ex-pastry chef at Nopa, has done an amazing job sourcing delicious and affordable wine. The space is adorable and it's the perfect place to spend a few hours getting to know your fellow Rockridgians (that's a term, right?)

The pastrami sandwich is a must have. Perfectly smoky, cured pastrami on thick, pillowy bread with just the right amount of cheese. I could eat this every day.</Review><user_name>Samantha Berg<//user_name>< gmap_id>

<rate>1<//rate>< Text>
The owner is quite welcoming, but definitely not the best shop out there. I took my car in for an alignment and tire mounting & balancing.

- I checked the alignment results and my car had -2.5 camber is the rear, which is far beyond normal for my car (BMW F30). He told me that there is no camber adjustment for the F30 platform, and my car had aggressive camber because I lowered my car. I asked other shops and BMW F30 owners and they all told me that there's camber adjustment in the rear.

- After getting my tires balanced, the car had CRAZY vibrations above 80 mph. Again he blamed it on my car and said that it was due to the spacers in the rear. I only put quality parts on my car. The spacers are from BMS, which is a reputable brand. I had to get my wheels rebalanced at a different shop, and the vibration went away.

If you care about your car, I wouldn't recommend this place AT ALL. Find a better shop that's more knowledgeable about cars.

+ I can't believe that the owner said that there is no camber adjustment in the rear because he owns the same car as me. He should know better.<//Text>

<user>110823748164668602652</user><review>I wouldn't recommend this place for the following reasons:
1. The first time I came and asked if they sold Kumho tires I was categorically told no which is false.
2. The second time I came, I provided specs for a front and rear tire and asked for pricing across different brands including Kumho. At this point the price that I was quoted was higher than American Tire Depot at Cypress, American Tire Depot at Downey and American Tire Depot at Santa Fe. I asked if he would price match and he mentioned no they don't price match other American Tire Depot stores, but he will price match other tire stores which is bogus. It basically shows you how this place is being run.
3. Using the psychological powers of influence and selling he went on to give more inaccurate information. He first not only mentioned the tires are in limited stock (this is accurate given Covid-19 has impacted production across tire manufacturers), but economy tires like Kumho will no longer be manufactured (bogus). Second, he went on to mention he was selling his tires at invoice pricing and the price he was providing was invoice pricing. Again, more bogus. Yes the pricing American Tire depot stores provide is an invoice price, but invoice for who? Invoice price for the customer, not the store.

I believe and understand there are costs to order and ship which increases retail cost when 1 tire for the front and back are purchased, but please don't use nonsensical scarcity tactics and give false information that your store first doesn't sell Kumho tires.

This store barely has any business. When asked about a patch that I'd happily tip his guy, as I have in other stores, he mentioned I'd have to wait an hour. After waiting an hour he didn't call at which point I decided to leave and take my business to American Tire Depot.

< Text>
From our experience, this business is unethical and takes advantage of people unfamiliar with vehicle maintenance. My mother took her car in with a chief complaint of replacing the shock absorbers, explaining that the car had been very shaky as of late--which she explicitly told a worker by the name of F. Huerta. Huerta instead decided to replace parts that my mother was not interested in replacing and didn't even address the shock absorbers, charging an astronomical total of $3200.95. He passed off his work by using confusing mechanical jargon, being unclear that the shock absorbers were NOT in fact replaced. My mother believed it was replaced all this time. After noticing that the car was still very shaky, we returned and told them that the shaking was continuing. After examining the car, Huerta shrugged and snapped that this place did not replace shock absorbers. What? There is even a sign hanging inside that reads "Struts and Shock," so of course we thought that this shop replaced shock absorbers. He should have informed my mother upfront that they do not replace shock absorbers and then told her of others parts he believes should be replaced, giving her OPTIONS like an ethical and moral mechanic would do. My mother was not interested in replacing other parts, as they were not emergent.

Furthermore, in the "Reason for Visit" section of the receipt, he wrote "2 tires RH alignment lower control arms sway bar links and 2 front axles, with power flush. Note rec front and rear struts and shock." This is a complete lie. My mother is unfamiliar with vehicle maintenance, so how would she have known to say to replace all these specific parts? This is unethical as this section should be what the CUSTOMER says. Huerta even admitted that he was in the wrong in writing the treatment plan in this section when the chief complaint my mother made should have been written.

We also looked up the price for these individual parts and discovered that Huerta overcharged parts by nearly double. A control arm was quoted for $489.99 (not even including the labor) on my receipt but was sold for $250 retail. When asked about this price gouging, Huerta sneered and simply retorted that his source ‚Äúisn‚Äôt online.‚Äù We took our car to a different mechanic in Buena Park and asked them about the inflated price and he replied that yes, Huerta indeed overcharged for these parts and that he himself wouldn‚Äôt have billed us this much.

Especially during the pandemic, $3200.95 is A LOT of money. This is MUCH more than the average American's rent. It speaks volumes about this business's morals and ethics (the lackthereof) that they are taking advantage of an Asian American woman's low vehicle maintenance knowledge. Would they have done the same if it were a man who instead came with the same issue? She put her trust in the hands of F. Huerta, only to be sneered at and taken advantage of, overcharging on replacements she didn't ask for nor was she told about and given options. It's akin to you going to a dentist with a complaint of tooth pain that needs a root canal. The dentist treats other teeth with small cavities but not the tooth that actually hurts, and when you complain about he ongoing pain, he says he doesn't do root canals.

TLDR: American Tire Depot Buena Park is an unethical and immoral shop that vastly overcharges parts and takes advantage of those who are unfamiliar with vehicle maintenance. They did NOT address my mother‚Äôs chief complaint with the car and instead replaced other parts she was uninterested in, using mechanical jargon to confuse her into thinking it was replaced. <UserId.>102164137254552309710</UserId.><user_name>Kevin Abadilla<//user_name><time>1582924426607</time><Rate>5</Rate>< review>
Came here to change out my tires since I had a big gash on the sidewall of one of my tires. Before I called these guys, I had called 5 other shops who didn‚Äôt have my tires in stock and couldn‚Äôt get them until the next business day. William who helped me out, said he could get them in 2 hours.

Took my car over and they started working on it. Come to find out that the wheel that had the gash on it also had a chunk of the rim missing from the rims edge on the inside part of the wheel. They wanted to throw the spare on but my subwoofer are bolted down to the trunks floor board so I said no and asked if my tire would hold. They pressure tested it and found it was ok but highly suggested I get a replacement ASAP and to bring it back and they‚Äôd take care of it.

Called the shop I got my wheels from, Salinas tires in La Mirada, to find out they stopped making my wheels. Also turns out my wheels were fake! (I posted it on yelp but that‚Äôs a whole other story). Got replacement rims the next day and brought it back. William felt bad because of all of my troubles and got the work done quick!

Honestly the best customers service from a tire shop I‚Äôve ever received. They didn‚Äôt try and bs me or charge me for stuff I didn‚Äôt need like charging me to remove and install the tpms sensors which my car doesn‚Äôt have! (Again, Salinas tires did that to me).

I am definitely coming back here for my car needs!!!

Only thing is that their company name is ‚ÄúAmerican Tire Depot‚Äù but their signs say ‚Äútires 4U‚Äù which was confusing especially when i tried to find the place. But that doesn‚Äôt change my rating or review on this place. More of a heads up to anyone looking for this place lol!< /review>

This place is popular! Be prepared to wait in line! However, the line moves quickly. One thing I feel they could do different is to change their system in regards to their waiting list. I'm from a foreign place and I just happened to stop in this McDonalds for a quick bite. These are the things I noticed. #1. Active on site security inside the establishment. I felt like I was being scrutinized. I assume shady things go on here. #2. I found out this McDonalds is located in an area called skid row. #3. The price of the food here is above the average price of the rest of the united states of america. #4. There isn't really a lot of friendly interaction between the clerk and the guest as well. For the most part this is what I gathered from this place. Taking into account that it was the first and only time I've been there. Not a good representation for Los Angeles for it being so close to the Greyhound bus station portal. If its any consolation , I received my food hot and it was good.< /Review>

<rate>4</rate><name>John L. Kerr< /name><text>If you are visiting this particular McDonald's you'll notice that you are very nearly in the middle of the strange no-man's (or woman's) land encompassing skid row and the new upwardly trendy lofts and shops that seek to define Download Los Angeles. This McDonald's manages to straddle this uncomfortable melange quite nicely. The inside of the restaurant was bright and clean. The counters looked new and the menu sign actually was orderly laid out with sensible photos next to the main items. I don't eat fast food often and the overhead menus always confuse me with "super" this and "extra large" that... I know that I am not getting the best price - ever. But this menu seemed far simpler, we ordered and our food was served quickly (with my special request done just right). We ate in and the table was clean as was the floor. It's true we were approached twice by people asking for money, but they were not intrusive and I had the feeling the manager and staff were well aware of who was in the restaurant and I didn't feel uncomfortable at all. The staff was so attentive that for the first time I actually filled out the online survey just to compliment them. That's quite a compliment in itself coming from me.</text><UserId.>107444994278293202314< /UserId.><date>1502873394373< /date>< Resp>
